        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "MOOC",
          "Probability of Answering the Next Question Correctly",
          "Correct (1) v Incorrect (0)",
          "1361 DBE-KT22 undergraduate learners, 18066 XES3G5M-T learners",
          "1 Relational Databases course and a 3rd grade maths course ",
          "Question Sequences, Knowledge Concepts, Question Text",
          "[Knowledge Concepts, Questions, Responses]",
          "Most KT models tend to ignore textual data, images and interactions. \n\nIn addition, these moels usually struggle with the cold-start problem. Finally, the authors claim that KT models struggle with interpretability.\n\n",
          "The proposed model integrates a language model in the KT task - using the text of questions and answers.\n\n",
          "The authors use a MLM (masked language model). This model takes as input the sequences of questions, answers and knowledge component text. These are encoded to create the LKT - the embeddings.\n\nThe embeddings are subsequently used as input to the prediction of probability of correctedness.",
          "BERT, ALBERT, DistilBERT, RoBERTa, ELECTRA, ERNIE-2.0, DeBERTa-v3, DKT, DKVMN, SAKT, GKT, AKT ",
          "5-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "DBE-KT22\n{AUC: 0.7984 - AKT, Accuracy: 0.7983 - AKT}\n\nXES3G5M-T\n{AUC: 0.8513 - DeBERTa-v3 Accuracy: 0.8421 - DeBERTa-v3 }",
          "Authors propose an LKT approach on 2 Datasets and show that, for one of them, their LKT approach (using a language model to include the text of the questions, answers and knowledge components.\n\nMoreover, when addressing the cold-start problem, the authors show that the model outperforms DKT on when the sequence is small.",
          "- No Ablation Study of different components of the PLS\n\n- Small set of datasets tested\n\nDoes not include other forms of multimodal data (logs, images, etc…)"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 7
    }
